dspace-development.title: Match arks to ProQuest Dissertation XML

comments.body:
[This](https://github.com/jrgriffiniii/etd-processor) already does the trick!  We should move this into the pulibrary GitHub organization.

I [converted Don's sample marc XML into an mrc file using MarcEdit](https://guides.library.illinois.edu/c.php?g=463460&p=3168159) and ran this script on it.  It got the arks for 77 of the records and placed the other three into a separate .mrc file.  The .mrc files can also be converted back to marc XML if needed after the arks were added, and the arks remain.

We should also make note in [this repo](https://github.com/pulibrary/dissertation_lookup) that the etd-processor should be used instead.

Leaving this in Review/QA for the new year, so that we can review and close as a team after confirming with stakeholders.

orangelight.title: Ensure the GA4 migration follows previously set GA settings

comments.body: Will look into this the week of 12/26.

We looked with @carolyncole and @mzelesky the utf-8 error issue. 
We identified:
1.  that the scsb-process-records method which lives in bibdata even though it has a [bad-utf8?](https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/blob/e216a5573c858569ab133ae3821c9b0bb445c1e1/app/models/scsb/partner_updates.rb#L147) method it didn't prevent the specific scsb record to get indexed. https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/SCSB-4026061 https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/issues/2052
3. The [bad_utf8](https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/blob/e216a5573c858569ab133ae3821c9b0bb445c1e1/app/models/scsb/partner_updates.rb#L26) array does nothing. It would be good to collect the scsb ids that are from a bad_utf8? record.
4. locally with vi we wrote the csv file to a new _fix csv file. In this file we searched and deleted manually the SCSB record that was logged through the SQL COPY process. We saved the file and scp it to catalog-indexer1.
5. In catalog-indexer1 I ran the rake task to upload the fixed call_numbers file to postgres. The call-numbers upload finished successfully and [call-numbers](https://catalog.princeton.edu/browse/call_numbers?search_field=browse_cn&q=) are back in the catalog.
6. I will repeat the same cleanup for the alma_orangelight_name_titles.csv

Next steps:
- [x] Email Columbia about this record. 
- [ ] Look if we can do a utf8 cleanup before the truncate method in the rake task. https://github.com/pulibrary/orangelight/issues/3306
- [x] Meet with @acozine to search for files in catalog-indexer1 that take too much space and can be deleted. 
- [x] Pause the rake tasks in catalog-indexer1 until: 
**1.** we figure out how to prevent copying non utf-8 records **2.** fix the space issue in catalog-indexer1

We worked with @acozine and @kayiwa  on the spacing issue and identified:
1. The log files were very large because the sneakers service is throwing errors https://github.com/pulibrary/orangelight/issues/3305 . 
2. As a workaround and until we fix this error @kayiwa: 
      i.  Increased the disk volume in all the catalog VMs, production, staging and qa. 
      ii. Updated the log rotation settings https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/pull/3555

Browse lists were recovered.
New tickets were created to address the cause.

pdc_describe.title: Moving curator to an ActiveRecord relation to make it more consistent with other work relationships

comments.body:
Probably hold off on reviewing this until #771 is reviewed and merged: It handles part of the testing, and I've merged that branch into this.

Looking at your comments, I was unsure about this:
> That said we should make it all constant.

Do you mean that immutable objects are good? Generally, I'd agree, but when it's just breaking the constructor down into smaller pieces, using private methods, I'm ok with it.

The more important thing to me is that a set of methods are consistent about whether they modify the object, or return a new object, but these methods were doing both.

pdc_describe.title: Store metadata as json, not a string blob in a json field

comments.body:
> I'd have a strong preference to only use `json` in names when we're dealing with a string that contains data serialized as JSON... If we actually have a hash, change names to reflect that.
> 
> Slight preference to stay with `:` in hashes.

We can not stay with ":" in hashes because the json hash does not include symbols.  That change is required.

These are not ruby hashes exactly, which is why I am still calling the json.  How about `json_hash`?

@astrochun Do you have an example of a report you have already gotten from Dspace?  It would be helpful to see what you are getting.

> @astrochun Do you have an example of a report you have already gotten from Dspace? It would be helpful to see what you are getting.

This is what [`dspace-osti`](https://github.com/pulibrary/dspace-osti) dumps from the DataSpace JSON API: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/pulibrary/dspace-osti/main/data/dspace_scrape.json

The above payload is pulled currently from the DataSpace API endpoint defined [here](https://github.com/pulibrary/dspace-osti/blob/2b074352da4943711e2c16faa1a7243d36d1e730/Scraper.py#L125).  

The collection IDs used to populate that string are defined in [this array](https://github.com/pulibrary/dspace-osti/blob/2b074352da4943711e2c16faa1a7243d36d1e730/Scraper.py#L16-L30).
